f =E2=80=98We can recreate society. We can recreate ourselves. We can do an=
ything we want.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
You might hear those very same optimistic calls today. We=E2=80=99re in the=
 transition from Industrial Society to Informational Society, from nation-s=
tate to individual. We=E2=80=99re emerging from a global catastrophe, a pan=
demic this time instead of a war. There=E2=80=99s a strong =E2=80=9Cwe can =
recreate society and ourselves and do anything we want=E2=80=9D breeze blow=
ing.=C2=A0
But there comes a point in every story when those who were fighting to gain=
 power gain it, and need to begin the hard work of ruling. When they=E2=80=
=99re no longer the underdog, but the ones in charge. My guess is that exis=
tentialism is going to make a comeback as people realize that self-sovereig=
nty is a double-edged sword.
There is no one else to blame. =E2=80=9CWe are left alone, without excuse.=
=E2=80=9D That is what Sartre meant when he said, =E2=80=9CMan is condemned=
 to be free.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
At the time of Sartre=E2=80=99s lecture in 1946, that was potentially funda=
mentally true -- people could choose what to do at any moment -- but not ve=
ry practical. If people wanted to stay alive, they needed to find work and =
do as they were told. If they wanted to fit in their communities, they need=
ed to attend church. Sartre would call this living inauthentically, but it =
was the practical reality. As a well-educated person from a well-to-do fami=
ly, he could afford to =E2=80=9Clive authentically.=E2=80=9D Many couldn=E2=
=80=99t.=C2=A0
Even today, the ability to not have to rely on oneself for employment is re=
served for the lucky ones. The richest countries in the world have the lowe=
st rates of self-employment. The United States has the lowest self-employme=
nt on the list at 6.3%
With the rise of the creator economy, entrepreneurship, remote work, and we=
b3, more people are pushing for the right to fend for themselves, to set th=
eir own course, make their own decisions, and bear responsibility for their=
 own actions. I=E2=80=99m all for it. I work for myself, as a creator, from=
 home, and I am putting more and more of my time, net worth, and energy int=
o web3.=C2=A0
If these trends continue, and if web3 challengers disrupt more incumbents [=
https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuhDAMQE8z2Q3Kd2AWWXTTa6B8DESFBCVOEb=
dvZlBbybJlW9aTnzMIc8qn3lNB8kojnjvoCEdZAREyqQXyGLxmDz4IJZ_Ea-nZoAYSyjhlgM2EV=
WOuQPZq1-AMhhTfF5RyRRY9yUFNg-ulFQw4ezI3scF6YaT0_OnVxTXVB4gONHxDPlMEsuoFcS83=
8XHjny2O4-hiQptyiHPnUhvtr_GS7j6UXHcsd1zgt4FcSNCcckafvGdcKSo73hk-eAuDlMIIb5z=
sFPd1smm7SbrNvCvVFjTuqwE2kvUfsK2_FrPB-l60V8dWtxoDniNEY1fwlwW8ZL69jDNEyE2yHw=
02hYL3sheMCsqvr5sm-ZL54D1pZJ_aVfyH_gCdDo2s], if better APIs and infrastruct=
ure make it easier for anyone to build their own products and businesses, i=
f more people work at home, away from bosses, individuals will have a great=
er ability to shape how the world works than at any point in modern human h=
istory. If you=E2=80=99re reading this, you=E2=80=99re likely going to be i=
nvolved in that shaping. That=E2=80=99s an immense amount of freedom, and w=
ith it comes an immense amount of responsibility.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re going to need to make the transition -- maybe in the next cou=
ple years, maybe in the next couple of decades -- from plucky, YOLO-ing und=
erdogs to the people responsible for how things work. We=E2=80=99ll rely on=
, and get to blame, others less than we ever had. We=E2=80=99ll get to make=
 our own decisions.=C2=A0
This is one of the reasons I=E2=80=99m a maximalist minimalist. Fighting ov=
er whose blockchain better serves the under 100M people in web3 today inste=
ad of figuring out a responsible path towards working together to onboard t=
he next billion users feels silly and inauthentic. And it=E2=80=99s not jus=
t blockchain maximalism, but maximalism of all sorts. Whenever I see maxima=
lism or dogma, I see people who aren=E2=80=99t ready to handle their freedo=
m and make their own meaning.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s not to say that we should all act in our own self-interest w=
ith disregard for others or that we shouldn=E2=80=99t join communities. Exi=
stentialism is not a selfish philosophy. Particularly after the war, Sartre=
 realized that existentialism needed to cope with togetherness, community, =
and even morality. In Existentialism is a Humanism, he wrote that people sh=
ould make choices as if they=E2=80=99re making that choice for the whole hu=
man race, asking, =E2=80=9CAm I really a man who has the right to act in su=
ch a manner that humanity regulates itself by what I do?=E2=80=9D
Any philosophy for the modern era will need to cope with the idea that our =
freedom is embedded together, that more than ever, society will be bottoms-=
up versus top-down. If we want to decrease institutional power, we also low=
er institutional responsibility. We=E2=80=99ll need to be responsible for e=
ach other. A modern philosophy will need to confront the fact that we need =
to create meaning for ourselves, but that life is not meaningless. I hope t=
hat nihilism and hedonism don=E2=80=99t rule the day.=C2=A0
Last week, there was a meme on twitter about whether DAOs can fire people, =
kicked off by this tweet [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuOwyAMhk9T=
lhHPhixYjDTqNSICboqaQETMVLn9OK1GI1l-yNi_-YJHmEs93FZ2ZKcb8djAZXjtCyBCZW2HOqb=
oxFVaZfTAotNRWGNZ2sd7BVh9WhzWBmxr05KCx1Tye4JzadjDCSvEYKK4DtMdrNLBij4Io6wX3A=
5cfnR9iwlyAAc_UI-SgS3ugbjtF_V1kTcyfKXzoi6UlaqawtQqlkz5jh7bTonQWkhjjebDVfbcU=
HVRN1rxLTlLTnIp-CB7emO47mTnpY0TWK2VV9EH3RkZ230iAc3XWXZ7m2h3eJ6arLpccCo15Zna=
z4dfYXk36N8jxbXlhMcI2U8LxA8S_JB9QxpnyFCJeBw9Ek8le90rwdUfAmKmT7J0OiPlWGgq_4v=
-Ag-YjHo].=C2=A0=C2=A0
Turns out, people have been fired from DAOs, but I think it highlights the =
kind of challenges we=E2=80=99re going to face as things get more decentral=
ized, liquid, and chaotic. New norms, rules, and technology, like something=
 that tracks contributions on-chain, will help, but it will be more importa=
nt than ever for people to think about what it means to take responsibility=
 for themselves.
Existentialism isn=E2=80=99t perfect. But I think it=E2=80=99s a good start=
ing point. In the parlance of composability, it=E2=80=99s a philosophy lego=
 on top of which a distributed group of individual leaders can build. We ne=
ed modern philosophers -- much better philosophers than me -- to wrestle wi=
th modern questions. It would be foolish to be the generation with the most=
 individual agency and the least intentional thought about what to do with =
it.=C2=A0
No quest is more optimistic, since it declares that our destiny lies within=
 ourselves.
