0;">In <em>Existentialism is a Humanism</em>, Sartre disagrees wholehearted=
ly with that classification:</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid=
 #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>No doctrine is mor=
e <strong>optimistic</strong>, since it declares that man's destiny lies wi=
thin himself.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The Ancient Greek philosophers =
believed that everything, including humans, came with an essence pre-instal=
led. Essence, and then existence. In <em>Existentialism is a Humanism, </em=
>Sartre proposed that existentialists share the opposite belief: <strong>ex=
istence comes before essence</strong>. We are nothing until we decide what =
to be. Or as Sartre put it (he went heavy on &#8220;man,&#8221; it was a di=
fferent time):&nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc=
; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>If, however, it is true th=
at existence is prior to essence, <strong>man is responsible for what he is=
</strong>. Thus, the first effect of existentialism is that it <strong>puts=
 every man in possession of himself as he is</strong>, and <strong>places t=
he entire responsibility for his existence squarely upon his own shoulders<=
/strong>. And, <strong>when we say that man is responsible for himself, we =
do not mean that he is responsible only for his own individuality, but that=
 he is responsible for all men</strong>.&nbsp;</em></p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;=
">Existentialism was a product of its time. While Sartre was the first phil=
osopher to identify as an Existentialist, in the mid-20th century, the phil=
osophy dates back to the mid-19th century with Danish philosopher <a href=
=3D"https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8TlhExkJ8Fi7ZSN132AMgBJ4=
OSQERIq9y-zGRRybJlPz09-bOYaY7p0ns8Mns2k6-ddKDfY6WcKbHzoGS8000LvVByYE5L1_SqZ=
_4wUyLa0K86p5PYfo6rt5h9DC8H56DYQ6PjbhgBLExt5wiV7GDiHdpGcgXtcOfi6TwFS5p-KF0x=
EFv1I-f9qMRbBZ-lKNS_fvE7OY91THM5PfcyvitQH6K09z5RMF-e0kIzYnLMa-DQ8AG6BpTisoY=
aoXcj9VIKFA6trBW4cxrjVkm-zVAf53hktEtt48aSDjGPMfkwF3l54EbrSyjPmjK3M_h8GQo4ru=
RuDvnG-SJjZgqUCmZnMBeIAjrZiYYLDvffBZR84myhYyXZxeIK_6F_24yMGg" rel=3D"" styl=
e=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">S&#248;ren Kierkegaard</a=
>, who believed that each individual is responsible for giving meaning to h=
is or her own life and for living it authentically, or passionately and sin=
cerely.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">On a 2001 BBC Radio podcast, <em><a href=3D"https=
://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkU1r5DAMhn9NfAz-nNgHHxbKdJe2TFsKw56CYysZ08R=
ObWeX_Pt6Zg4FIQl98IpH1hSYYtr1GnNBV9eXfQUd4H-eoRRIaMuQeu80OVDJBFfIae6IFBL53I=
8JYDF-1iVtgNZtmL01xcdw28CYCnTRQikjjGCjlKNlcuRUMQyMWqXUqAi565rNeQgWNPyDtMcAa=
NaXUtbcsF8NPVaLK4Q2r7H4cW9tXGoJVp-jg5qxr9P5_TjgP787fH7ZHp8fzXnbG3bMvmEP6uGD=
fJxOr2_T1-HpL-PhXU77W0MPbu6HZIK91CGCvKaYEqxoR6gQmLe0NVS6ASTnzDBnLG8Fdds4VHW=
Ol4m2eRtyMfbzehBKOsQyxOTDVNufF7PAfGtUMn2NyxZ82XsIZpjB3aGVO_sbxn6CAKn-xPWmVO=
KMdrxjBDNM75AqVX5lf6Adqsou1q3wI_oNfnSZpQ" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a;=
 text-decoration: underline;">In Our Time: Philosophy: Existentialism</a></=
em>, University of London Reader in Philosophy, Dr. A.C. Grayling, describe=
d the conditions from which existentialist thought was born:&nbsp;</p><bloc=
kquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; mar=
gin-left: 1em;"><em>Scientific history, which was a product of German schol=
arship in the 19th century had called very very many things in question. Th=
at sense, also, that religious verities and religious sources for morality =
were under threat by the view that the whole universe was governed by natur=
al laws, not by transcendent ones. Then of course the development of Darwin=
ian theory. All that conspired together to give some of the philosophers of=
 the 19th century the sense that they had to look for a different ground of=
 value.</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; l=
ine-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">As Nietzsche put more succinctly, &#8=
220;God is dead.&#8221; The Enlightenment, to Nietzsche, closed the door on=
 the possibility of the existence of God. Until that point, people derived =
meaning and a set of rules from the existence of God and from religion. Wit=
hout God, then, from where were people to derive meaning and purpose?&nbsp;=
</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 1em 0;">Existentialism assumes that there is no God, and therefore tha=
t our existence comes before our essence. We exist, and then we make meanin=
g. If no one designed us, then we define ourselves by our actions. Now, I&#=
8217;m not dumb enough to weigh in on the existence of God in public -- thi=
s piece isn&#8217;t about God -- but I think that we&#8217;re in the middle=
 of an equally profound shift, and that it&#8217;s worth pausing for a mome=
nt to solidify our philosophical and moral footing before everything spins =
too fast and runs away from us.&nbsp;</p><h3 style=3D"-moz-osx-font-smoothi=
ng: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-=
family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI'=
, Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoj=
i', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: =
1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;"><strong>&#8220;Institutions are dead.&#82=
21;</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">If existentialism sprung from the need to make se=
nse of a world in which scientific progress called God into question, it ma=
y also fit a world in which technological progress is calling institutions =
into question.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">In 2017, <a href=3D"https://email.mg=
2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEluhTAMhk_zsgNlYugii256DZTBgeiRBGUo4vbNg0Uly7Y8_danZY=
E1pkscMRf0cUu5DhABzrxDKZBQzZAWZwQZ6cwG_oWM4IbMw4xcXmwC8NLtoqQK6Khqd1oWF8O9g=
